Customer Segmentation - Clustering¶

Plan¶

Lifecycle¶

Business Model Canvas¶

Use case¶

We want to perform a customer segmentation.

To do this, we want to divide the customers into individual equal segments according to characteristics that are relevant for the purchase.

These segments contain similar customer groups, which we can then separate.

This helps our company to adapt our products and marketing measures to these groups and thus to motivate customers to buy and to generate loyal customers.

Problem¶

We want to segment our customers to target our products and marketing more effectively in order to increase purchases und revenue.

Source

Relevant metrics¶

In this unsupervised, there are no explicit metrics against which the accuracy of the model can be measured, beacuse there is no truth label given with the feature vector.

However, we want a number of clusters that is logically meaningful and interpretable.

We will therefore follow the elbow method and try different values and then decide which ones make more sense with our problem in mind.

Model¶

The analysis of the data showed that income and spending score are the most suitable for clustering.

We therefore use these features to create a model with the K-means algorithm.

To find an optimal number of clusters, we use the elbow method.

Where the "elbow" flattens out, the best number of clusters can be read.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
inertia = []
for i in range(1,12):
    k_means = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=34, init='k-means++')
    k_means.fit(X)
    inertia.append(k_means.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(1,12), inertia)
plt.xticks(range(1,12))

The coherence of the clusters is measured with the value inertia, which is used to determine the quality of the clusters.

We see that 5 is indeed a good value to get the best ratio between the number of clusters and the inertia measure.

We now create a clustering based on the findings of the elbow method and additionally with the next two values, the 5 clusters from the elbow method and 4 and 6 for validation.

We see that for k = 4 we neglect the cluster in the upper left corner.

At k = 6, a cluster is created that alienates another cluster, which is not good for the validity of the model.

K = 5 seems to be the best value for the model.

In [ ]:
range_n_clusters = [4, 5, 6]

for n_clusters in range_n_clusters:
    # Create a subplot with 1 row and 2 columns
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    fig.set_size_inches(18, 7)

    # The 1st subplot is the silhouette plot
    # The silhouette coefficient can range from -1, 1 but in this example all
    # lie within [-0.1, 1]
    ax1.set_xlim([-0.1, 1])
    # The (n_clusters+1)*10 is for inserting blank space between silhouette
    # plots of individual clusters, to demarcate them clearly.
    ax1.set_ylim([0, len(X) + (n_clusters + 1) * 10])

    # Initialize the clusterer with n_clusters value and a random generator
    # seed of 10 for reproducibility.
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=10)
    cluster_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(X)

    # The silhouette_score gives the average value for all the samples.
    # This gives a perspective into the density and separation of the formed
    # clusters
    silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(X, cluster_labels)
    print(
        "For n_clusters =",
        n_clusters,
        "The average silhouette_score is :",
        silhouette_avg,
    )

    # Compute the silhouette scores for each sample
    sample_silhouette_values = silhouette_samples(X, cluster_labels)

    y_lower = 10
    for i in range(n_clusters):
        # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to
        # cluster i, and sort them
        ith_cluster_silhouette_values = sample_silhouette_values[cluster_labels == i]

        ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

        size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
        y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

        color = cm.nipy_spectral(float(i) / n_clusters)
        ax1.fill_betweenx(
            np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
            0,
            ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
            facecolor=color,
            edgecolor=color,
            alpha=0.7,
        )

        # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle
        ax1.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))

        # Compute the new y_lower for next plot
        y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples

    ax1.set_title("The silhouette plot for the various clusters.")
    ax1.set_xlabel("The silhouette coefficient values")
    ax1.set_ylabel("Cluster label")

    # The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values
    ax1.axvline(x=silhouette_avg, color="red", linestyle="--")

    ax1.set_yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks
    ax1.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1])

    # 2nd Plot showing the actual clusters formed
    colors = cm.nipy_spectral(cluster_labels.astype(float) / n_clusters)
    ax2.scatter(X.iloc[:, 0], X.iloc[:, 1], marker='*', s=30, lw=0, alpha=0.7,
                c=colors, edgecolor='k')

    # Labeling the clusters
    centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    # Draw white circles at cluster centers
    ax2.scatter(
        centers[:, 0],
        centers[:, 1],
        marker="o",
        c="white",
        alpha=1,
        s=200,
        edgecolor="k",
    )

    for i, c in enumerate(centers):
        ax2.scatter(c[0], c[1], marker="$%d$" % i, alpha=1, s=50, edgecolor="k")

    ax2.set_title("The visualization of the clustered data.")
    ax2.set_xlabel("Feature space for the 1st feature")
    ax2.set_ylabel("Feature space for the 2nd feature")

    plt.suptitle(
        "Silhouette analysis for KMeans clustering on sample data with n_clusters = %d"
        % n_clusters,
        fontsize=14,
        fontweight="bold",
    )

plt.show()

For n_clusters = 4 The average silhouette_score is : 0.4931963109249047
For n_clusters = 5 The average silhouette_score is : 0.553931997444648
For n_clusters = 6 The average silhouette_score is : 0.5376203956398481

The silhouette score is between 0 and 1, where 1 means that the cluster has the best density and the best separation. If the value is 0, it means that the clusters overlap.

We see with k = 6 that the red cluster number 5 has a low score and overlaps with the green cluster 3. 6 is therefore not a good value for k.

At k= 4 we see that clusters 1 to 3 have a good score, but cluster 0 is much wider compared to the other clusters. the width represents the size of the cluster, we aim to have clusters of equal size in the optimal case.

It has been confirmed that k = 5 is the best way to separate the customers.

We are now able to divide our customers into 5 different categories and ready to deploy the model in production.
